snippet.textDisplay:
WARNING from a vette owner (check my chnl).
I'm writing this to save some peoples savings. Very nice, in depth review but you shouldn't be so over excited. You should own a car for at least a few months or ask owners first.
I understand that you have to return the favor to Chevy but you won't buy back the cars of the people you influenced when they brake!
ofc vettes, when you put numbers down for comparison, are crazy deals, the mistake we all made. That would be the case if the cars would work as intended! We owned 2 new c7 Vettes. '14 and '19. It's not only the cheap plastic and inferior quality. They start to malfunction. From '14 to '19, chevy didn't fix c7's: Poping gear transmission, problematic infotainment, bad bose speakers breaking the turn signal sound, battery connections causing 'check real axle' lights, braking system overheating and so many more issues we're suffering from. So please don't compare supercars with vettes. Yes, the vette engines are a masterpiece but that's it. The engine only.

snippet.textDisplay: Don't see how in the world you gave it a 2 in the "Practicality" rating.  Compare the mpg to the other cars you have listed above it with the same rating...not even a comparison.  The Corvette just sips gas as you drive down the interstate and it's not bad in town either.  For this reason alone it should have scored at least a point higher than the other three cars listed above it.  What about serviceability and parts availability compared to the three cars you have listed above it?  Just compare the cost of an oil and filter change among the four cars and you once again see the "Practicality" of the Corvette. Also the resell value compared to exotics you have listed above it.  Sometimes an exotic can actually increase in value but the huge maintenance expense etc. can cause many of these cars to be driven very little each year. and they can experience, in short order, a re-sell price drop that's more than the entire cost of a Corvette.  The Corvette can easily be a daily driver...how's that for "Practicality"?  Don't know if you ever go back and re-evaluate your "Doug Score", but as far as I'm concerned you really missed the boat on this one.

snippet.textDisplay:
It's like SavageGeese said, they spent so long making the front-mid engine layout perfect (Yes Corvette's are technically already "Mid-Engined", they just were Front instead of Rear), made a bulletproof engine, made it practical with a huge hatchback and storage galore and decent gas mileage (For a spots car), comfortable and easy to drive, affordable, cheap to maintain, and all of it was due to the fact it was a relatively unchanged design for so many years.

And that long, imposing front end with the cockpit all the way in back, it might have been "Just another Corvette" but Corvette's have always been distinctive compared to literally any other car. Being Front-engines DEFINED it; It was an affront to those European Cars three times it's price it always sought to outdo, because it often did so by being completely "Out of the norm" compared to them.

Now? It definitely looks like a Supercar. Drives like one. Has lots of weird "Quirks and Features" like one. But it looks like every other "Mid-Engined Supercar". It looks generic now.

And the fact it's Rear-Mid Engined now means lots and lots of money to fix it. You wanna know why Boxters are such a bitch and five-quarters to fix? Thats not even mentioning the completely and totally redesigned . . . well, everything. Everything is completely new and almost nothing was really carried over. Thats all sorts of "What If's?" when it comes to dependability.

Can I still tell it's a Corvette? Yes because I'm a car person. Will others? Maybe, because it's big news and it's hard to miss. Lots will probably mistake it for something far more exotic with a lot less personality and history than Corvette's actually have. But for me, I'm disinterested either way. I'll stick with the C7.
